1
00:01:14,918 --> 00:01:18,285
<i>To find something, anything...</i>

2
00:01:18,455 --> 00:01:22,915
<i>... a great truth,
or a lost pair of glasses...</i>

3
00:01:23,393 --> 00:01:27,796
<i>... you must first believe there will be
some advantage in finding it.</i>

4
00:01:28,998 --> 00:01:31,466
<i>I found something a long time ago...</i>

5
00:01:31,634 --> 00:01:35,229
<i>... and have held on to it
for grim death ever since.</i>

6
00:01:35,405 --> 00:01:38,397
<i>I owe my success in life to it.</i>

7
00:01:38,575 --> 00:01:41,043
<i>It put me where I am today.</i>

8
00:01:41,211 --> 00:01:43,270
<i>This principle:</i>

9
00:01:44,781 --> 00:01:49,115
<i>What you don't know won't hurt you.</i>

10
00:01:52,255 --> 00:01:57,124
<i>They called it idealism
in a book I read.</i>

11
00:03:08,198 --> 00:03:11,190
<i>Get the gun.
Get the gun. Get the gun.</i>

12
00:03:15,572 --> 00:03:17,403
<i>Oh, my God.</i>

13
00:03:44,901 --> 00:03:46,300
The judge won't scare easy.

14
00:03:48,671 --> 00:03:51,799
I don't count on him scaring easy.

15
00:03:55,645 --> 00:03:58,011
You think it's beneath my dignity?

16
00:03:58,181 --> 00:03:59,944
Well, you're governor, they tell me.

17
00:04:00,116 --> 00:04:02,607
Yeah, I'm governor.

18
00:04:02,785 --> 00:04:05,948
The trouble with governors is they
think they gotta keep their dignity.

19
00:04:06,122 --> 00:04:08,818
There's nothing worth doing
a man can do to keep his dignity.

20
00:04:08,992 --> 00:04:10,516
Human frame ain't built that way.

21
00:04:12,395 --> 00:04:14,795
When I'm not governor anymore
because I'm president...

22
00:04:14,964 --> 00:04:17,524
...I wanna meet somebody at midnight,
I'll do that then too.

23
00:04:18,268 --> 00:04:20,759
Hope you leave me
to get a night's sleep.

24
00:04:20,937 --> 00:04:23,531
No, Jack, you going with me
because that's what you want.

25
00:04:24,040 --> 00:04:26,167
Yeah, you and Sugar
with me in the White House.

26
00:04:26,342 --> 00:04:29,175
I'll give Sugar a pistol range
right out there in the garden.

27
00:04:29,879 --> 00:04:32,677
Brace of Republican senators
can set up his tin cans for him.

28
00:04:32,849 --> 00:04:35,409
And I'm gonna appoint
a special member to Cabinet for you:

29
00:04:35,585 --> 00:04:39,351
Secretary to the Bedchamber
of Mr. Jack Burden.

30
00:04:40,356 --> 00:04:42,620
Somebody to keep them
telephone numbers straight...

31
00:04:42,792 --> 00:04:46,284
...and return their little pink silk articles
that get left behind.

32
00:04:48,064 --> 00:04:50,032
But we gotta do this first.

33
00:04:50,199 --> 00:04:53,293
In the middle of the night when we
could just do it in town sometime.

34
00:04:53,469 --> 00:04:56,370
Sometime ain't never now.

35
00:04:57,874 --> 00:04:59,967
Bastard.

36
00:05:01,010 --> 00:05:02,238
Which way up there?

37
00:05:04,681 --> 00:05:07,650
Jack, tell Sugar
how to get to the house.

38
00:05:08,184 --> 00:05:10,880
It's your people live down here.

39
00:05:27,837 --> 00:05:29,566
Suppose he don't open up?

40
00:05:31,341 --> 00:05:33,901
Make him. What I pay you for?

41
00:06:08,244 --> 00:06:10,144
Hey, Jack.

42
00:06:10,313 --> 00:06:12,281
Mr. Duffy.

43
00:06:13,282 --> 00:06:15,648
This is Willie Stark
from up Mason City.

44
00:06:15,818 --> 00:06:17,786
- County treasurer.
- Glad to meet you.

45
00:06:18,755 --> 00:06:21,121
<i>- Jack Burden.
- From The Chronicle.</i>

46
00:06:21,290 --> 00:06:22,780
Good to meet you, Mr. Burden.

47
00:06:22,959 --> 00:06:25,359
Yeah, Willie's on business
for Mason City.

48
00:06:25,528 --> 00:06:26,859
Bond issue them got up there.

49
00:06:27,030 --> 00:06:29,157
Gonna build a schoolhouse.

50
00:06:29,332 --> 00:06:33,063
Yeah. Me and Willie
was in school together.

51
00:06:33,236 --> 00:06:37,138
Oh, you was in school, Alex.
I didn't know.

52
00:06:37,306 --> 00:06:39,399
Not the teacher's favorite,
I don't expect.

53
00:06:39,575 --> 00:06:41,839
No, sir, that's true.

54
00:06:42,011 --> 00:06:45,242
Willie was, though.
Still is, ain't you, Willie?

55
00:06:45,415 --> 00:06:47,747
Yeah, Willie married
a schoolteacher.

56
00:06:48,818 --> 00:06:50,046
Well, you know...

57
00:06:50,219 --> 00:06:53,620
...they tell me that schoolteachers
are made with it...

58
00:06:53,790 --> 00:06:55,655
...in the same place as the rest.

59
00:06:56,325 --> 00:06:58,987
Now, is that right or not, Mr. Stark?

60
00:07:03,332 --> 00:07:05,391
Yeah, that's right.

61
00:07:08,337 --> 00:07:09,804
Slade!

62
00:07:09,972 --> 00:07:11,906
Beers all around.

63
00:07:12,075 --> 00:07:13,542
Not for me, thanks.

64
00:07:13,709 --> 00:07:16,473
Oh, that little schoolteacher
don't like it when you drink?

65
00:07:16,646 --> 00:07:19,274
Well, she don't favor it, for a fact.

66
00:07:22,051 --> 00:07:24,178
Well, beers all around.

67
00:07:24,821 --> 00:07:26,846
Well, I sell beer
to those who want it.

68
00:07:27,356 --> 00:07:29,881
I don't make nobody drink them.

69
00:07:30,626 --> 00:07:33,857
Well, maybe you got some
orange pop for him.

70
00:07:34,030 --> 00:07:35,258
That's what he wants.

71
00:07:36,699 --> 00:07:40,726
Yeah, I think I'd like some orange pop.
Two straws.

72
00:07:46,008 --> 00:07:48,306
Jack, get up Mason City.

73
00:07:48,478 --> 00:07:50,810
See who's this fella
who thinks he's Jesus Christ...

74
00:07:51,147 --> 00:07:53,809
...come down off the cross to scourge
the moneychangers...

75
00:07:53,983 --> 00:07:56,543
...out of that shinplaster courthouse
they got them there.

76
00:07:56,719 --> 00:07:59,449
I know who he is.
Fella with a Christmas tie...

77
00:07:59,622 --> 00:08:01,055
...pushed a school bond through.

78
00:08:01,524 --> 00:08:03,719
- You know him?
- Met him.

79
00:08:03,893 --> 00:08:06,020
Watched him drink
a bottle of orange pop once...

80
00:08:06,195 --> 00:08:09,358
...through two straws on account
of a wife who don't favor drinking.

81
00:08:09,532 --> 00:08:11,693
She favor him
staying parish treasurer?

82
00:08:11,868 --> 00:08:13,733
Don't you know
how things are run up there?

83
00:08:13,903 --> 00:08:16,167
Run up there
like they're run down here.

84
00:08:16,339 --> 00:08:21,242
Yeah? Well, you leave down here
and run on up there.

85
00:08:29,152 --> 00:08:32,178
As a commissioner, as chairman,
I guess you're in a position...

86
00:08:32,355 --> 00:08:35,017
...to know the situation
regarding the schoolhouse contract.

87
00:08:35,191 --> 00:08:36,419
Ain't no situation.

88
00:08:36,592 --> 00:08:38,423
Maybe not, but maybe so.

89
00:08:38,594 --> 00:08:40,357
Ain't any situation.

90
00:08:40,863 --> 00:08:42,125
Board took a bid offer.

91
00:08:42,298 --> 00:08:44,391
A.J. Moore's bid, the fella's name...

92
00:08:44,567 --> 00:08:46,660
...schoolhouse gets built.

93
00:08:46,836 --> 00:08:49,168
This Moore fella's bid,
I take it, was the lowest?

94
00:08:49,672 --> 00:08:51,401
Now, you lookie here.

95
00:08:51,574 --> 00:08:54,566
Ain't nobody tells a board
what bid to take.

96
00:08:54,744 --> 00:08:57,679
Anybody can come along
put in a little pissant bid.

97
00:08:57,847 --> 00:08:59,178
Board doesn't have to take it.

98
00:08:59,348 --> 00:09:01,475
Board takes somebody
who can do the work right.

99
00:09:01,651 --> 00:09:03,175
Ain't nothing done but legal.

100
00:09:03,352 --> 00:09:06,116
Who was it
put in the little pissant bid?

101
00:09:06,289 --> 00:09:09,190
- Name of Jeffers, if I recollect.
- Jeffers Construction?

102
00:09:09,358 --> 00:09:12,156
- Yeah.
- Well, that's a real firm, a big firm.

103
00:09:13,029 --> 00:09:16,123
The board picks
who can do the work right.

104
00:09:16,299 --> 00:09:18,824
That's all I got to say.

105
00:09:19,468 --> 00:09:20,696
Don't you wanna tell mama...

106
00:09:20,870 --> 00:09:23,668
...you wanna see yourself
shining in the table? No?

107
00:09:23,839 --> 00:09:27,331
All right. I wish I could have
sold some to you.

108
00:09:27,510 --> 00:09:30,274
Be out of your way in a second here.
And no brushes, you sure?

109
00:09:30,446 --> 00:09:31,743
- I'm sure.
- All right.

110
00:09:31,914 --> 00:09:34,405
Thank you.
Thank you for your time. Bye-bye.

111
00:09:34,584 --> 00:09:35,812
Mr. Stark.

112
00:09:38,454 --> 00:09:42,322
Why, Mr. Jack Burden,
how are you, sir?

113
00:09:42,491 --> 00:09:45,824
You know, people would think
parish treasurer paid well enough...

114
00:09:45,995 --> 00:09:49,089
...a man wouldn't have to sell
household fix-it kits door-to-door.

115
00:09:49,265 --> 00:09:52,166
- People would think.
- Doesn't in Mason City.

116
00:09:52,335 --> 00:09:55,361
Well, I'm maybe not so good
at mathematics...

117
00:09:55,538 --> 00:09:57,733
...as some other parish treasurers
you may've met.

118
00:09:57,907 --> 00:10:00,034
Or too good at it.

119
00:10:00,676 --> 00:10:03,304
How much they steal
on the schoolhouse contract?

120
00:10:03,479 --> 00:10:05,174
Well, let's see... .

121
00:10:05,781 --> 00:10:08,614
Jeffers come in $ 142,000.

122
00:10:08,784 --> 00:10:11,082
Moore, $ 175,000.

123
00:10:11,254 --> 00:10:15,384
That's $33,000 split six ways,
5500 per commissioner.

124
00:10:15,558 --> 00:10:19,756
They done it so plain and pretty, well,
you'd almost have to admire them.

125
00:10:19,929 --> 00:10:22,591
Just point out Jeffers
uses nigra laborers...

126
00:10:22,765 --> 00:10:25,632
...skilled men, you know?

127
00:10:25,801 --> 00:10:29,498
Next thing, it's, "Lookie here, nigras
making more money than you men.

128
00:10:29,672 --> 00:10:31,606
Pushing wheelbarrows,
hauling dirt."

129
00:10:32,575 --> 00:10:36,067
And that's it. "Goodbye, Mr. Jeffers
and your low bid.

130
00:10:36,245 --> 00:10:39,146
You go build your nigra schoolhouse
somewhere else."

131
00:10:39,315 --> 00:10:42,216
Not that you didn't try and get people
to see what was going on.

132
00:10:42,385 --> 00:10:46,822
Oh, I yelled so long and loud about
these old boys lining they pockets...

133
00:10:46,989 --> 00:10:49,287
...I'm lucky to have
any job in Mason City:

134
00:10:49,458 --> 00:10:51,551
Government, door-to-door,
or any other variety.

135
00:10:51,727 --> 00:10:53,558
I stood out there
on that street corner...

136
00:10:53,729 --> 00:10:55,720
...pencil in one hand,
paper in the other...

137
00:10:55,898 --> 00:10:57,889
...trying to show people
the numbers.

138
00:10:58,067 --> 00:11:00,763
But you stop people out there
in that hot sun...

139
00:11:00,936 --> 00:11:03,166
...try to show them arithmetic...

140
00:11:03,339 --> 00:11:05,500
...well, they can't see it so clear...

141
00:11:05,675 --> 00:11:09,042
...through the sweat pouring in they
own eyes from they own hard labor.

142
00:11:09,211 --> 00:11:12,044
Especially if you put nigras
in the equation.

143
00:11:12,214 --> 00:11:15,047
- Why, you're likely to get beat up.
- Likely?

144
00:11:15,217 --> 00:11:17,310
Once or twice.

145
00:11:18,154 --> 00:11:19,587
You gonna run again in November?

146
00:11:19,755 --> 00:11:24,590
No, I'm done. A lame duck. Lucy too.
They got her fired from teaching.

147
00:11:24,760 --> 00:11:28,594
And I don't care. I don't want to teach
there just so they can steal money.

148
00:11:28,764 --> 00:11:32,200
That's right. You're looking at your
own private two-person leper colony.

149
00:11:32,368 --> 00:11:33,995
Sipping pop.

150
00:11:34,603 --> 00:11:36,537
So, what are you gonna do, then?

151
00:11:36,706 --> 00:11:41,871
I don't know. String my pa a fence,
slop some pigs, milk some cows.

152
00:11:45,314 --> 00:11:49,478
I'm gonna keep the faith, Mr. Burden,
that's what I'm gonna do.

153
00:11:50,019 --> 00:11:54,285
I'm gonna keep the faith
in the people, because you know why?

154
00:11:56,092 --> 00:11:58,219
Time...

155
00:11:58,394 --> 00:12:01,761
...brings all things to light.

156
00:12:02,365 --> 00:12:04,765
I trust it's so.

157
00:12:38,601 --> 00:12:39,966
Joe.

158
00:12:40,136 --> 00:12:42,161
Did you get a photograph of him?

159
00:12:42,338 --> 00:12:43,828
Who?

160
00:12:47,076 --> 00:12:49,567
The next mayor of this town.

161
00:13:01,223 --> 00:13:03,748
You know what people are saying?

162
00:13:04,627 --> 00:13:07,221
People are saying
that God himself had a hand...

163
00:13:07,396 --> 00:13:10,388
...in this schoolhouse business.

164
00:13:10,566 --> 00:13:15,299
That God stepped in
on Willie Stark's side.

165
00:13:15,838 --> 00:13:20,332
Yes, sir. He does work
in mysterious ways sometimes.

166
00:13:20,509 --> 00:13:22,409
Sometimes...

167
00:13:22,578 --> 00:13:25,411
...he has somebody else do it.

168
00:13:25,581 --> 00:13:30,450
Sends over a fat man in a striped suit
with a big car to do his will.

169
00:13:30,619 --> 00:13:34,055
Well, I have had
some worse employers, I admit that.

170
00:13:35,191 --> 00:13:37,022
What you want?

171
00:13:37,460 --> 00:13:40,452
Well, I wanna work for you,
Mr. Stark.

172
00:13:40,629 --> 00:13:44,065
And you wanna work for the people,
unless I been misinformed.

173
00:13:44,233 --> 00:13:46,497
People vote me,
I'd be privileged to serve them.

174
00:13:46,669 --> 00:13:50,628
- What, as the county treasurer?
- Yes, sir.

175
00:13:52,208 --> 00:13:54,699
Mr. Stark, you could run
for mayor of Mason City...

176
00:13:54,877 --> 00:13:58,404
...and you could win without climbing
out of bed in the morning.

177
00:13:58,581 --> 00:14:00,310
You just put the word out...

178
00:14:00,749 --> 00:14:04,617
...about Willie Stark, who tried to take
on the crooks single-handed...

179
00:14:04,787 --> 00:14:07,119
...Willie Stark,
who tried to warn us...

180
00:14:07,289 --> 00:14:12,090
...Willie Stark, who could have saved
our kids if we'd have just listened.

181
00:14:12,995 --> 00:14:18,524
Now, I'm not talking about Willie Stark
for the mayor of Mason City. No, sir.

182
00:14:18,701 --> 00:14:21,192
I'm talking about Willie Stark...

183
00:14:21,370 --> 00:14:26,171
...as the next governor
of the great state of Louisiana.

184
00:14:27,843 --> 00:14:31,335
Now, you saw a man
holding out a handful of cash to you...

185
00:14:31,514 --> 00:14:33,414
...and you said no.

186
00:14:33,582 --> 00:14:35,174
This is what I see.

187
00:14:35,351 --> 00:14:37,819
I see a man in a booth...

188
00:14:37,987 --> 00:14:40,922
...Iooking down at a ballot,
a working man.

189
00:14:41,090 --> 00:14:46,221
And he sees three names there:
Harrison, MacMurphy and Stark.

190
00:14:46,629 --> 00:14:48,358
Now, what this man really sees...

191
00:14:48,531 --> 00:14:51,500
...is that picture in the newspaper
of them three little coffins...

192
00:14:51,934 --> 00:14:55,028
...and the one man since
the great Governor Stanton died...

193
00:14:55,204 --> 00:14:58,833
...that had the guts to buck the powers
that killed them.

194
00:15:00,142 --> 00:15:02,440
Now, that man, that voting man,
he's got a pencil...

195
00:15:02,611 --> 00:15:04,738
...he checks a box,
you wake up governor.

196
00:15:05,114 --> 00:15:07,708
And that little lady lying
beside you...

197
00:15:07,883 --> 00:15:12,183
...the one that don't favor liquor...

198
00:15:12,621 --> 00:15:15,522
...she wakes up the governor's wife.

199
00:15:20,663 --> 00:15:22,221
That's what I see.

200
00:15:23,699 --> 00:15:27,999
Now, why don't you take a minute
with your orange pop...

201
00:15:29,471 --> 00:15:31,769
...see if you can't see it too...

202
00:15:33,375 --> 00:15:35,070
...governor.

203
00:16:04,740 --> 00:16:06,571
You got your speech?

204
00:16:06,809 --> 00:16:08,538
All right.

205
00:16:12,114 --> 00:16:14,014
Willie Stark!

206
00:16:19,455 --> 00:16:21,355
Thank you, folks.

207
00:16:23,258 --> 00:16:24,816
Thank you kindly.

208
00:16:26,629 --> 00:16:28,995
My name's Willie Stark
from Mason City yonder...

209
00:16:30,432 --> 00:16:33,993
...and I'm pleased to have a chance
to talk with you all here today.

210
00:16:34,169 --> 00:16:36,137
Now, friends...

211
00:16:36,972 --> 00:16:40,703
...what I wanna talk about is
something that's been troubling me.

212
00:16:40,876 --> 00:16:43,674
- Coffee, please.
- Yes, ma'am.

213
00:16:48,017 --> 00:16:50,281
Can I sit with you?

214
00:16:50,452 --> 00:16:52,010
Or anything else.

215
00:16:53,355 --> 00:16:55,016
No, thanks.

216
00:16:55,658 --> 00:16:58,684
- You don't like my looks?
- I don't care about anybody's looks...

217
00:16:58,861 --> 00:17:00,852
...but I can't recall
ever going for anyone...

218
00:17:01,030 --> 00:17:03,555
...who reminds me
of a box of spilled spaghetti.

219
00:17:04,099 --> 00:17:07,262
Miss Burke, I'm sitting here
having a cup of coffee.

220
00:17:07,436 --> 00:17:09,734
I'm almost through,
then you couldn't sit with me...

221
00:17:09,905 --> 00:17:12,840
...which is what you asked for.
- Sorry.

222
00:17:15,744 --> 00:17:17,473
Not working
for Sen-Sen Puckett anymore.

223
00:17:18,047 --> 00:17:21,210
- Now, he wasn't a bad-Iooking fellow.
- Heel.

224
00:17:21,383 --> 00:17:23,613
Well, sure, politically and elsewise.

225
00:17:23,786 --> 00:17:25,617
Who didn't know that?

226
00:17:25,788 --> 00:17:28,018
I guess I'm slower on some things
than others.

227
00:17:28,190 --> 00:17:30,090
- Like you.
- Am I?

228
00:17:30,259 --> 00:17:32,386
- I think so.
- I think not.

229
00:17:32,561 --> 00:17:33,823
Not on this charade.

230
00:17:35,264 --> 00:17:37,892
That's the topic of the interview.

231
00:17:38,067 --> 00:17:40,797
Then tell me, if you're so smart.

232
00:17:40,969 --> 00:17:44,837
All right. Harrison's a city man,
MacMurphy's a cracker.

233
00:17:45,007 --> 00:17:47,805
Not a cracker precisely,
but enough of one to worry Harrison...

234
00:17:47,976 --> 00:17:49,341
...that crackers won't know
the difference.

235
00:17:49,511 --> 00:17:53,072
So Harrison looks for someone
to split the cracker vote.

236
00:17:53,248 --> 00:17:55,944
Hears about an honest man
up in Crackerville...

237
00:17:56,118 --> 00:17:58,586
...where some cracker kids go down
with a fire escape...

238
00:17:58,754 --> 00:18:01,621
...that was supposed to be stuck with
more than spit to their schoolhouse.

239
