00:51:44,444 --> 00:51:45,672
I wouldn't know about that.

724
00:51:45,846 --> 00:51:49,612
Only way to not know
is to not wanna know.

725
00:51:51,384 --> 00:51:55,115
I'm retired, Mr. Stark. A reporter
asked my opinion and I gave it.

726
00:51:55,288 --> 00:51:58,519
If you was retired, no reporter
would wanna ask you anything.

727
00:51:59,626 --> 00:52:01,753
What you say matters.

728
00:52:02,062 --> 00:52:04,724
A lot more than you pretend it don't.

729
00:52:06,566 --> 00:52:08,557
So I'm asking you...

730
00:52:09,469 --> 00:52:11,403
...call off the dogs.

731
00:52:12,506 --> 00:52:17,375
Asking is different than telling
and that sounded like telling to me.

732
00:52:18,111 --> 00:52:20,136
Didn't it to you, Jack?

733
00:52:24,518 --> 00:52:26,816
You been a judge a long time.

734
00:52:26,987 --> 00:52:28,614
Yes, I have.

735
00:52:30,690 --> 00:52:33,158
How would it feel, do you think...

736
00:52:34,394 --> 00:52:36,919
...to not be one no more?

737
00:52:40,200 --> 00:52:43,465
No man has ever been able
to intimidate me.

738
00:52:43,637 --> 00:52:47,437
I said what I said and I see no reason
to say or think anything different.

739
00:52:48,241 --> 00:52:52,143
Despite your expositions
on laws and men, sir.

740
00:52:54,748 --> 00:52:55,976
Suit yourself.

741
00:52:57,250 --> 00:53:00,981
You're right, Jack.
He don't scare easy.

742
00:53:03,356 --> 00:53:08,623
Judge, it's more in pain
than wrath I go.

743
00:53:09,196 --> 00:53:12,359
Let's go.
It's past Sugar Boy's bedtime.

744
00:53:13,533 --> 00:53:15,501
Your employer is calling you, Jack.

745
00:53:16,336 --> 00:53:19,305
I wouldn't go around
advertising this visit to anyone.

746
00:53:19,472 --> 00:53:21,269
In case you change your mind.

747
00:53:31,751 --> 00:53:33,480
Bastard.

748
00:53:34,387 --> 00:53:37,982
Well, Jackie,
you got a job cut out for you.

749
00:53:38,592 --> 00:53:42,028
- MacMurphy.
- No, the judge.

750
00:53:43,496 --> 00:53:45,464
You bring down the lion...

751
00:53:45,632 --> 00:53:49,500
...the rest of the jungle will quake
in fear and they'll all fall into line.

752
00:53:50,103 --> 00:53:53,334
- I won't find anything.
- Oh, yes, you will.

753
00:53:53,540 --> 00:53:58,204
A man is conceived in sin
and born in corruption...

754
00:53:58,378 --> 00:54:01,836
...and passeth from the stink of
the didie to the stench of the shroud.

755
00:54:03,917 --> 00:54:05,782
You'll find something.

756
00:54:06,620 --> 00:54:08,178
And make it stick.

757
00:54:16,796 --> 00:54:20,527
<i>Apart from pleasing the boss,
I could see little advantage...</i>

758
00:54:20,700 --> 00:54:26,366
<i>... in finding anything beyond what
was already known about Judge Irwin.</i>

759
00:54:29,142 --> 00:54:32,305
<i>What was known
was that he was kind to you...</i>

760
00:54:32,479 --> 00:54:36,210
<i>... when your father left you
and your mother without saying why.</i>

761
00:54:38,718 --> 00:54:40,583
<i>What was known
was that he taught you...</i>

762
00:54:40,754 --> 00:54:43,222
<i>.... the things your father
should have:</i>

763
00:54:44,291 --> 00:54:46,418
<i>How to be a gentleman.</i>

764
00:54:46,626 --> 00:54:49,220
<i>How to firmly shake a hand.</i>

765
00:54:49,729 --> 00:54:53,426
<i>How to safely load a shotgun
and lead a duck if you wanted to hit it.</i>

766
00:54:57,237 --> 00:54:59,171
<i>What was known...</i>

767
00:54:59,673 --> 00:55:03,541
<i>... was that he was more of a father
to you than your real father...</i>

768
00:55:05,712 --> 00:55:08,146
<i>... who you didn't know at all.</i>

769
00:56:34,100 --> 00:56:36,068
Hold it, please.

770
00:56:36,603 --> 00:56:38,867
Governor's penthouse.

771
00:56:43,777 --> 00:56:46,837
How you doing digging
something up on Judge Irwin?

772
00:56:47,213 --> 00:56:48,703
Nothing.

773
00:56:48,915 --> 00:56:51,145
Nothing. Found nothing
or done nothing?

774
00:56:51,317 --> 00:56:55,344
There was nothing to find. I could
dig to China, wouldn't find anything.

775
00:56:55,522 --> 00:56:57,353
- And I'm not framing him.
- Framing?

776
00:56:57,524 --> 00:56:59,549
Ain't nobody talking about framing.

777
00:56:59,726 --> 00:57:01,091
That's never necessary.

778
00:57:01,261 --> 00:57:04,253
The truth is always sufficient.
You just find the truth.

779
00:57:04,664 --> 00:57:06,188
It's a waste of time and money.

780
00:57:06,366 --> 00:57:08,834
Jesus, doesn't anybody listen
to what I say anymore?

781
00:57:09,002 --> 00:57:12,563
You don't wanna do it, don't do it.
Or are you just looking for a raise?

782
00:57:13,273 --> 00:57:16,174
I'm gonna give you $ 100 raise
whether you want it or not.

783
00:57:16,342 --> 00:57:17,934
If I wanted more money, I'd make it.

784
00:57:19,913 --> 00:57:21,938
You gonna tell me
you work for me for love?

785
00:57:22,115 --> 00:57:25,016
I don't know why I work for you,
but it ain't for love or money.

786
00:57:25,185 --> 00:57:26,584
Well, that's right, it's not.

787
00:57:27,487 --> 00:57:29,717
And you don't know why.

788
00:57:31,724 --> 00:57:33,123
But I do.

789
00:57:34,527 --> 00:57:35,926
Why?

790
00:57:36,262 --> 00:57:41,063
Boy, you work for me
because I'm the way I am...

791
00:57:41,234 --> 00:57:43,600
...and you the way you are...

792
00:57:43,770 --> 00:57:47,729
...and that's just an arrangement
founded in the natural order of things.

793
00:57:55,548 --> 00:57:57,914
She sure could skate.

794
00:58:01,588 --> 00:58:03,317
Right now...

795
00:58:03,857 --> 00:58:06,121
...hidden away in chambers...

796
00:58:06,593 --> 00:58:09,721
...not out here in the open
like you and me...

797
00:58:10,897 --> 00:58:14,298
...there's a legislature
full of hyena-headed...

798
00:58:14,467 --> 00:58:17,903
...belly-dragging sons of bitches...

799
00:58:18,138 --> 00:58:21,767
...setting around trying to figure out
how to impeach me.

800
00:58:23,309 --> 00:58:26,472
Now, they say it's because
I got crooks on the payroll.

801
00:58:26,646 --> 00:58:28,511
I say, "Is that all?"

802
00:58:29,616 --> 00:58:32,585
Of course I got them.
I got a can of oil in the garage too...

803
00:58:32,752 --> 00:58:34,515
...because there ain't a machine
made by man...

804
00:58:34,687 --> 00:58:39,090
...don't need a squirt of that
from time to time just to keep running!

805
00:58:41,861 --> 00:58:44,091
But my crooks...

806
00:58:45,298 --> 00:58:47,493
...unlike theirs...

807
00:58:47,667 --> 00:58:50,568
...are all atremble...

808
00:58:50,803 --> 00:58:53,169
...to be too crooked.

809
00:58:54,040 --> 00:58:57,771
They're itty-bitty compared
to their crooks in there.

810
00:58:57,944 --> 00:59:00,412
The Standard Oil
and the power companies.

811
00:59:00,580 --> 00:59:02,775
Besides, I got my eye on mine.

812
00:59:02,949 --> 00:59:05,577
Ain't nobody watching
over these crooks.

813
00:59:06,186 --> 00:59:09,212
Ain't nobody got their eye on them...

814
00:59:09,389 --> 00:59:13,758
...while they rob
the resources of this state!

815
00:59:15,195 --> 00:59:17,993
Who made that son of a bitch
what he is? Who made him governor?

816
00:59:18,164 --> 00:59:20,598
And he goes and two-times me?
I'll kill him.

817
00:59:21,067 --> 00:59:23,763
No, he's two-timing Lucy.

818
00:59:23,937 --> 00:59:27,134
You need some other kind of
arithmetic for what he's doing to you.

819
00:59:27,307 --> 00:59:30,367
Lucy, she's a fool. She's... .

820
00:59:31,344 --> 00:59:33,904
- I don't know what.
- His wife.

821
00:59:35,048 --> 00:59:38,916
A hick with a college degree
from some Baptist hole in the ground.

822
00:59:41,387 --> 00:59:43,184
What was she like?

823
00:59:44,157 --> 00:59:47,217
- I didn't know Lucy any further back--
- The slut on skates.

824
00:59:48,528 --> 00:59:50,860
I don't know,
I was looking at her skates.

825
00:59:51,030 --> 00:59:53,021
Sure you were.

826
00:59:55,401 --> 00:59:58,564
- Was she pretty?
- Look, just forget it.

827
01:00:00,006 --> 01:00:01,906
How young was she?

828
01:00:02,809 --> 01:00:05,573
- Who cares?
- Look at me.

829
01:00:20,760 --> 01:00:25,060
He'll be back.
The world is full of sluts on skates.

830
01:00:26,899 --> 01:00:31,302
Skates, grass skirts, geisha outfits.

831
01:00:37,076 --> 01:00:39,101
Contortionists.

832
01:00:42,348 --> 01:00:46,614
<i>Every man a king
Every man a king</i>

833
01:00:46,786 --> 01:00:50,950
<i>For you can be a millionaire</i>

834
01:00:51,124 --> 01:00:55,117
<i>But there's something
Belonging to others</i>

835
01:00:55,295 --> 01:00:59,095
<i>Well, there's enough
For all people to share</i>

836
01:00:59,532 --> 01:01:03,901
<i>When it's sunny June
Or December too</i>

837
01:01:04,070 --> 01:01:07,471
<i>In the wintertime or spring</i>

838
01:01:08,141 --> 01:01:10,234
<i>Well, there'll be peace without end</i>

839
01:01:10,410 --> 01:01:12,742
<i>Every neighbor a friend</i>

840
01:01:12,912 --> 01:01:16,575
<i>With every man a king</i>

841
01:01:23,790 --> 01:01:27,282
The judge married money.
Savannah money.

842
01:01:27,460 --> 01:01:30,088
The daughter of an industrialist
out there.

843
01:01:30,263 --> 01:01:32,231
<i>He's clean, Willie.
He's washed in the blood.</i>

844
01:01:34,634 --> 01:01:38,195
- You call yourself a detective.
- I'm most certainly not--

845
01:01:38,371 --> 01:01:41,135
The son of a bitch
is washed in whitewash!

846
01:01:41,307 --> 01:01:42,968
- Wanting it isn't the same as being it.
- I know!

847
01:01:43,142 --> 01:01:45,633
- I can feel it.
- That isn't the same either.

848
01:01:45,812 --> 01:01:47,677
Where did you find this itty-bitty out?

849
01:01:47,847 --> 01:01:49,712
Hall of Records. It's all there.

850
01:01:49,882 --> 01:01:52,180
Marriage licenses,
property deeds, public record.

851
01:01:52,352 --> 01:01:56,118
The public record is for the public,
not us. That's why it's called that.

852
01:01:56,289 --> 01:01:58,018
You ain't gonna find nothing there!

853
01:01:58,958 --> 01:02:01,518
Now, I told you to dig,
not scuff your shoe a little bit.

854
01:02:01,677 --> 01:02:05,010
- You gotta get out and talk to them.
- To whom?

855
01:02:05,481 --> 01:02:07,176
The public.

856
01:02:07,717 --> 01:02:09,446
The people who knew him.

857
01:02:09,618 --> 01:02:11,108
This was a long time ago.

858
01:02:11,287 --> 01:02:15,621
Well, look, he's still alive, isn't he?
Causing trouble.

859
01:02:15,791 --> 01:02:18,783
So you gotta chafe up your hands
a little, for chrissake...

860
01:02:18,961 --> 01:02:21,122
...like the rest of us.

861
01:02:26,635 --> 01:02:29,035
Where the hell is everybody?

862
01:02:29,839 --> 01:02:33,639
<i>Whatever there was to find
in the case of the upright judge...</i>

863
01:02:33,809 --> 01:02:36,607
<i>... would be long-buried
in the past...</i>

864
01:02:36,779 --> 01:02:39,680
<i>... like a dead cat in the back yard.</i>

865
01:02:42,685 --> 01:02:44,550
<i>But what could be buried there
like that...</i>

866
01:02:45,855 --> 01:02:48,551
<i>... in a place like Burden's Landing?</i>

867
01:02:48,924 --> 01:02:51,415
<i>Where you and your friends
grew up...</i>

868
01:02:51,594 --> 01:02:55,360
<i>... shaded
by 300-year-old live oaks...</i>

869
01:02:55,564 --> 01:02:58,124
<i>... and the sense
of your own entitlement.</i>

870
01:02:59,735 --> 01:03:04,365
<i>To dig around that past
in that back yard...</i>

871
01:03:04,607 --> 01:03:10,273
<i>... you must first- - You tell yourself.
- seek out the girl from that past:</i>

872
01:03:10,813 --> 01:03:12,678
<i>Anne Stanton.</i>

873
01:03:12,848 --> 01:03:15,544
<i>The daughter of the governor
back then.</i>

874
01:03:15,885 --> 01:03:18,979
<i>The little sister
of your best friend, Adam...</i>

875
01:03:20,656 --> 01:03:22,385
<i>... who, one day, you noticed...</i>

876
01:03:22,558 --> 01:03:25,493
<i>... and it struck you
kind of all of a sudden...</i>

877
01:03:25,661 --> 01:03:28,027
<i>... wasn't little anymore.</i>

878
01:03:30,866 --> 01:03:34,063
<i>She was the first one
you loved like that.</i>

879
01:03:34,503 --> 01:03:37,336
<i>And the last, it turns out.</i>

880
01:03:39,475 --> 01:03:41,943
<i>So you hold on to her pictures
in your mind...</i>

881
01:03:42,678 --> 01:03:44,509
<i>... year after year...</i>

882
01:03:44,680 --> 01:03:48,810
<i>... in the belief that someday
it'll be like that again...</i>

883
01:03:48,984 --> 01:03:51,418
<i>... even though
you have no evidence.</i>

884
01:03:53,422 --> 01:03:55,287
<i>In church, they call this faith.</i>

885
01:03:57,159 --> 01:03:59,218
<i>So that's what I'll call it.</i>

886
01:03:59,762 --> 01:04:03,289
Every month or so,
I come out here and light a fire.

887
01:04:03,532 --> 01:04:05,523
Dry the place out.

888
01:04:08,103 --> 01:04:11,004
I know it doesn't really
accomplish that...

889
01:04:11,173 --> 01:04:14,700
...but I got a feeling if I didn't,
if nobody ever came...

890
01:04:15,711 --> 01:04:18,179
...the place would just one day
cave in on itself.

891
01:04:19,014 --> 01:04:20,572
Adam never comes out?

892
01:04:20,749 --> 01:04:22,774
No. Not anymore.

893
01:04:23,986 --> 01:04:26,978
He took the piano, or someone did.

894
01:04:27,189 --> 01:04:30,488
Took it and put it in that place
he's living. Have you seen it?

895
01:04:32,928 --> 01:04:36,694
God forbid my brother
ever spent any money on himself.

896
01:04:37,032 --> 01:04:39,159
Or that people knew it.

897
01:04:42,605 --> 01:04:44,505
How's your wife?

898
01:04:44,740 --> 01:04:47,800
I'm sorry, I've forgotten her name.

899
01:04:49,245 --> 01:04:51,713
That didn't quite work out
as I'd hoped.

900
01:04:52,882 --> 01:04:55,476
A lot of tangled bedclothes
and unspoken loathing...

901
01:04:55,651 --> 01:04:57,983
...then spoken loathing
and no tangled bedclothes.

902
01:05:00,422 --> 01:05:03,391
Didn't I read of your engagement
in the society column?

903
01:05:03,559 --> 01:05:07,086
Which you know
I always turn to first in the paper.

904
01:05:07,830 --> 01:05:10,492
I was engaged. More than once.

905
01:05:11,634 --> 01:05:13,101
Adam didn't care for any of them.

906
01:05:14,303 --> 01:05:18,034
- Why that should matter, I don't know.
- Who needs them, anyway?

907
01:05:25,548 --> 01:05:30,485
Anne, way back,
was Judge Irwin ever broke?

908
01:05:31,720 --> 01:05:32,948
What?

909
01:05:33,389 --> 01:05:35,823
Judges don't make
the kind of money your father did...

910
01:05:35,991 --> 01:05:37,856
...or my father,
or anyone who lives here.

911
01:05:38,561 --> 01:05:41,530
Why on earth would you want
to know such a thing?

912
01:05:41,697 --> 01:05:45,224
- Someone asked me and I didn't know.
- Asked you what?

913
01:05:45,801 --> 01:05:47,701
What I just asked you.

914
01:05:47,870 --> 01:05:49,428
Why?

915
01:05:52,141 --> 01:05:54,132
Oh, Jack,
what are you doing for that man?

916
01:05:54,310 --> 01:05:57,040
- That man.
- Whatever it is, don't.

917
01:05:57,212 --> 01:06:00,340
That man is what those pushed
away from the trough call him.

918
01:06:00,516 --> 01:06:04,043
Those invited to it
should find another name.

919
01:06:04,219 --> 01:06:06,779
Accepting state money
for scholarships...

920
01:06:06,956 --> 01:06:09,015
...is different
from being on his payroll.

921
01:06:09,191 --> 01:06:12,217
- Is it?
- Yes, it is.

922
01:06:17,266 --> 01:06:19,928
- Oh, don't ruin it.
- What?

923
01:06:20,402 --> 01:06:22,029
Don't ruin this?

924
01:06:22,204 --> 01:06:25,765
Or that fine, beautiful time
we all had here once?

925
01:06:26,809 --> 01:06:28,936
You sure that's what it was?

926
01:06:29,878 --> 01:06:33,871
- Yes.
- Then why did it turn into this time?

927
01:06:34,483 --> 01:06:37,418
With me drinking myself to death...

928
01:06:37,586 --> 01:06:40,953
...Adam getting more reclusive
and strange...

929
01:06:41,123 --> 01:06:44,889
...and you once a month coming out
to a house with the electricity cut off?

930
01:06:46,028 --> 01:06:48,496
This time came from that time.

931
01:06:51,634 --> 01:06:53,363
We should go.

932
01:06:55,104 --> 01:06:56,503
The fire can burn.

933
01:06:57,239 --> 01:06:59,469
It will anyway, you know, one day.

934
01:06:59,642 --> 01:07:01,075
What will what anyway?

935
01:07:02,811 --> 01:07:05,211
Cave in on itself.

936
01:07:06,782 --> 01:07:08,511
Everything.

937
01:08:06,909 --> 01:08:09,742
Is the Seaboard Bank in Savannah?

938
01:08:09,912 --> 01:08:12,642
Not since 1938.

939
01:08:12,981 --> 01:08:14,778
What happened in '38?

940
01:08:14,950 --> 01:08:17,817
Bought out by Georgia Fidelity.

941
01:08:18,220 --> 01:08:20,688
Got any idea
who was president then?

942
01:08:21,423 --> 01:08:23,254
Franklin Roosevelt.

943
01:08:24,693 --> 01:08:28,129
Ma'am, of the bank.

944
01:08:28,363 --> 01:08:31,389
LeMoyne Carruthers was my friend.

945
01:08:31,734 --> 01:08:33,599
A dear friend.

946
01:08:34,670 --> 01:08:39,869
And his daughter, Mabel,
well, I did what I could for her...

947
01:08:40,042 --> 01:08:43,375
...even after her financial reversal.

948
01:08:45,013 --> 01:08:48,540
The year of her financial reversal
was roughly what?

949
01:08:48,717 --> 01:08:50,685
She threw that inheritance away.

950
01:08:51,220 --> 01:08:53,688
Two or three notes I paid myself.

951
01:08:53,889 --> 01:08:56,722
For the memory of LeMoyne,
my dear friend.

952
01:08:56,892 --> 01:09:02,023
But she'd come back at me without
shame and say, "I want money."

953
01:09:02,197 --> 01:09:06,395
For parties and balls
and to adorn herself.

954
01:09:06,568 --> 01:09:09,469
For she was plain, to be kind.

955
01:09:09,738 --> 01:09:11,797
Then she was broke
when she met the judge.

956
01:09:12,141 --> 01:09:14,939
So was he. This is when
he was still attorney general...

957
01:09:15,110 --> 01:09:17,578
...under Governor Stanton
pulling down 3400 a year...

958
01:09:17,746 --> 01:09:22,410
...while paying off liens on his place
on the Row to the tune of 42,000.

959
01:09:23,886 --> 01:09:26,616
Well, you see there,
you are a detective.

960
01:09:26,789 --> 01:09:28,416
You dug and chinked
the metal box...

961
01:09:28,590 --> 01:09:31,718
...and are enjoying the sound of it
a bit, if I'm not mistaken.

962
01:09:31,894 --> 01:09:33,225
Might still be empty.

963
01:09:33,395 --> 01:09:35,386
No, it's full.

964
01:09:35,564 --> 01:09:38,192
Crawling with maggots
by now, maybe...

965
01:09:38,367 --> 01:09:41,632
...but still a little something they was
chewing on. Just have to look.

966
01:09:41,837 --> 01:09:44,635
Still have to find the key.
And that ain't gonna be easy.

967
01:09:44,840 --> 01:09:47,604
Well, there's nothing easy
that means anything.

968
01:09:47,776 --> 01:09:49,573
You'll do it. I have faith.

969
01:09:51,246 --> 01:09:53,578
I like this one, Slade.

970
01:09:56,118 --> 01:10:01,420
Now, they all is yelling that I got
no right to what's on their table.

971
01:10:01,590 --> 01:10:04,423
What's on their table is theirs.

972
01:10:05,327 --> 01:10:08,296
I'm not trying to take it.

973
01:10:08,463 --> 01:10:11,694
"Go ahead, sit down at that table,"
I tell.

974
01:10:12,034 --> 01:10:15,470
"Have all you want to eat.
Eat till you can't eat no more.

975
01:10:15,637 --> 01:10:19,505
Now, what's left on that table...

976
01:10:19,675 --> 01:10:22,838
...when you can't eat no more,
even if you tried...

977
01:10:23,011 --> 01:10:28,244
...leave that there
because that's for the rest of us."

978
01:10:30,986 --> 01:10:35,150
And for that, they're trying to ruin me.

979
01:10:35,324 --> 01:10:37,849
For taking
what they left on the table...

980
01:10:38,026 --> 01:10:41,518
...and using it
to build something for you!

981
01:10:42,331 --> 01:10:46,461
To build 3000 miles
of paved highways...

982
01:10:46,635 --> 01:10:50,628
...a hundred and eleven new bridges,
208 new schools...

983
01:10:50,806 --> 01:10:54,367
...60,000 brand-new jobs!

984
01:10:59,915 --> 01:11:02,611
Now, they wanna ruin me...

985
01:11:05,520 --> 01:11:07,954
...because they wanna ruin you.

986
01:11:09,625 --> 01:11:14,289
But your will is my strength.

987
01:11:15,197 --> 01:11:18,655
Your need is my justice.

988
01:11:18,834 --> 01:11:23,100
And I won't let them!

989
01:11:35,317 --> 01:11:38,013
It come to me in a dream.

990
01:11:38,387 --> 01:11:41,686
Whilst you were up in Savannah with
your pail and shovel, eating oysters.

991
01:11:41,857 --> 01:11:43,085
What did?

992
01:11:43,725 --> 01:11:47,354
I'm gonna build me
the best-staffed, best-equipped...

993
01:11:47,529 --> 01:11:50,498
...biggest goddamn health center
this state ever saw.

994
01:11:50,666 --> 01:11:54,193
This country ever saw.
The All-Father hisself.

995
01:11:54,369 --> 01:11:58,305
You want me to do what
to further this noble enterprise?

996
01:11:58,473 --> 01:12:00,532
Deliver me my chief of staff.

997
01:12:00,709 --> 01:12:03,507
Fine. You give me a list
of who you're thinking to run it.

998
01:12:03,679 --> 01:12:05,112
Only one name on it:

999
01:12:05,614 --> 01:12:07,445
Dr. Adam Stanton.

1000
01:12:07,616 --> 01:12:11,950
That's my boy, Tom! That's the way!
You see that?

1001
01:12:12,154 --> 01:12:16,921
That's an all-American pass.
Goddamn it. Attaboy, Tom!

1002
01:12:22,764 --> 01:12:26,598
Well, somebody gotta
run this hospital.

1003
01:12:26,768 --> 01:12:29,202
He's gotta be the best, don't he?

1004
01:12:29,371 --> 01:12:32,772
- Adam Stanton is not the best.
- Well, he is for what I need.

1005
01:12:32,941 --> 01:12:34,909
They'll never approve
the money otherwise.

1006
01:12:35,644 --> 01:12:37,305
Willie, Adam's an old friend of mine.

1007
01:12:37,479 --> 01:12:39,606
As I certainly know,
else I wouldn't be asking.

1008
01:12:39,781 --> 01:12:41,806
I know him and I know you.
He won't do it.

1009
01:12:42,317 --> 01:12:44,012
What's wrong with me?

1010
01:12:44,186 --> 01:12:46,313
To him, what isn't?

1011
01:12:46,488 --> 01:12:48,456
You're everything
his father fought against.

1012
01:12:48,623 --> 01:12:50,818
He hates what you represent,
if not you yourself.

1013
01:12:51,393 --> 01:12:53,884
I'm not asking him to love me.

1014
01:12:54,062 --> 01:12:56,292
- I'm asking him to run a hospital.
- Your hospital.

1015
01:12:56,465 --> 01:12:59,832
The people's hospital, where any poor
redneck and nigger can get the best...

1016
01:13:00,002 --> 01:13:02,368
...without paying a dime.
He ought to like that.

1017
01:13:02,537 --> 01:13:06,769
No. What you're asking is for him
to put his family's name next to yours.

1018
01:13:06,942 --> 01:13:09,410
So you can trot him out
in front of senators and say:

1019
01:13:09,578 --> 01:13:11,944
"Lookie here,
lookie who I got standing next to me.

1020
01:13:12,114 --> 01:13:15,277
The son of the most honorable man
who ever served this state."

1021
01:13:15,450 --> 01:13:17,179
Just get him.

1022
01:13:24,860 --> 01:13:27,158
Not easy being the son
of a great man.

1023
01:13:29,264 --> 01:13:32,358
It don't look so hard
for my boy Tom out there.

1024
01:13:34,169 --> 01:13:35,966
Far as you know.

1025
01:13:47,215 --> 01:13:49,012
We should go.

1026
01:13:50,218 --> 01:13:53,949
Not yet. Let's go in again.

1027
01:14:09,838 --> 01:14:12,466
<i>The friend of your youth...</i>

1028
01:14:13,008 --> 01:14:15,909
<i>... is the only friend you'll ever have.</i>

1029
01:14:16,078 --> 01:14:18,376
<i>For he doesn't really see you.</i>

1030
01:14:20,382 --> 01:14:24,910
<i>He sees in his mind a face,
which doesn't exist anymore.</i>

1031
01:14:25,087 --> 01:14:26,952
<i>And speaks a name- -</i>

1032
01:14:27,122 --> 01:14:32,856
<i>Spike, Bud, Red, Rusty, Jack.</i>

1033
01:14:33,195 --> 01:14:37,359
<i>- that belongs
to that now nonexistent face.</i>

1034
01:14:38,700 --> 01:14:42,136
<i>He's still the young idealist
you used to be.</i>

1035
01:14:42,437 --> 01:14:45,770
<i>Still sees good and bad
in black and white...</i>

1036
01:14:46,108 --> 01:14:49,236
<i>... and men as sinners or saints,
but never both.</i>

1037
01:14:49,411 --> 01:14:52,437
<i>- Hey, Adam.
- Feels superior in the knowledge....</i>

1038
01:14:52,614 --> 01:14:55,344
<i>... that you no longer
can distinguish the two.</i>

1039
01:14:55,517 --> 01:14:57,712
<i>- Jack.
- That's what drives you to it...</i>

1040
01:14:57,886 --> 01:15:00,320
<i>- ... try to stick the knife in.
- Come on in.</i>

1041
01:15:00,489 --> 01:15:03,890
<i>For there's a kind
of snobbery in failure.</i>

1042
01:15:04,059 --> 01:15:07,119
<i>Like the twist
to the mouth of a drunk.</i>

1043
01:15:09,397 --> 01:15:10,762
You're looking good, Jack.

1044
01:15:10,932 --> 01:15:13,332
Thank you.
I'll take that as a compliment.

1045
01:15:16,872 --> 01:15:18,737
Been playing much?

1046
01:15:19,107 --> 01:15:20,904
Who wants to know, my sister?

1047
01:15:21,376 --> 01:15:23,503
It was just a question.

1048
01:15:24,312 --> 01:15:28,942
- Everything good?
- Yes, Jack, everything's good.

1049
01:15:29,251 --> 01:15:31,617
All right.
I'm gonna tell you something.

1050
01:15:31,786 --> 01:15:35,153
I don't want you to start yelling at me
until I'm finished.

1051
01:15:35,590 --> 01:15:37,455
Governor Stark
wants you as director...

1052
01:15:37,626 --> 01:15:40,288
...of the medical center he's building.
Whatever you want...

1053
01:15:40,862 --> 01:15:43,330
...all you have to do is say,
it's yours.

1054
01:15:43,498 --> 01:15:44,988
- Money?
- I didn't say that.

1055
01:15:45,167 --> 01:15:48,864
What do I want money for?
I got everything I want. Look around.

1056
01:15:49,037 --> 01:15:50,265
I didn't say money.

1057
01:15:50,438 --> 01:15:53,271
Then what?
What's next when that doesn't work?

1058
01:15:53,441 --> 01:15:55,966
- A threat of some kind?
- Of course not.

1059
01:15:56,144 --> 01:15:58,544
That's how he gets things done?
What he relies on?

1060
01:15:58,713 --> 01:16:00,271
The bribe and the threat?

1061
01:16:00,582 --> 01:16:04,518
I would never do that to you
or let anyone else. You know that.

1062
01:16:05,053 --> 01:16:07,351
I don't know what you think
he's thinking, Jack...

1063
01:16:07,522 --> 01:16:10,889
...or what you're thinking,
but couldn't be flattery.

1064
01:16:11,059 --> 01:16:14,119
He's thinking what he thinks about
anybody he wants something from...

1065
01:16:14,296 --> 01:16:16,526
...who doesn't wanna give it.
- Something from their past.

1066
01:16:16,965 --> 01:16:19,991
- You just said he wasn't.
- Not their past, their weakness.

1067
01:16:20,168 --> 01:16:22,261
- Same thing.
- No, it isn't.

1068
01:16:22,437 --> 01:16:25,463
I'm not gonna debate it with you, Jack.
We're not in school anymore.

1069
01:16:25,640 --> 01:16:28,871
I don't care if you know I'm right.
I don't care if I am right. But I am.

1070
01:16:32,881 --> 01:16:35,372
Then what is it, Jack?
What is my weakness?

1071
01:16:36,851 --> 01:16:38,910
You can't look at anybody
with something broke...

1072
01:16:39,087 --> 01:16:40,645
...without wanting to fix it.

1073
01:16:40,822 --> 01:16:43,188
- And that's a weakness?
- Some would say.

1074
01:16:43,358 --> 01:16:44,586
You would say.

1075
01:16:45,627 --> 01:16:47,720
- It's no disgrace.
- Well, then tell me, Jack.

1076
01:16:47,896 --> 01:16:49,921
Tell me, please.
How is that a weakness?

1077
01:16:51,433 --> 01:16:54,197
- I don't need to tell you.
- I think you do.

1078
01:16:54,369 --> 01:16:57,338
If you don't know, I'll leave you
to think about it. It'll come to you.

1079
01:16:57,505 --> 01:17:00,065
No, it won't, Jack.
And you'll have to go to your boss...

1080
01:17:00,242 --> 01:17:02,836
...and tell him you failed
without taking out the big guns.

1081
01:17:03,011 --> 01:17:06,276
So tell me, for your sake,
how is that a weakness?

1082
01:17:06,448 --> 01:17:09,246
Because it makes you do things
you don't wanna do.

1083
01:17:09,417 --> 01:17:11,317
If they're good.

1084
01:17:11,486 --> 01:17:14,216
And this is. He may not be...

1085
01:17:15,257 --> 01:17:16,986
...but this is.

1086
01:17:30,372 --> 01:17:32,397
It was good to see you, Adam.

1087
01:18:04,794 --> 01:18:09,049
Now, before I tell y'all the story
about how this great university...

1088
01:18:09,735 --> 01:18:12,259
...changed the life of a boy
from Mason City...

1089
01:18:12,279 --> 01:18:14,879
...who, by all rights,
should still be swilling hogs...

1090
01:18:16,019 --> 01:18:19,369
...first, I'm gonna set your minds at ease
on another point of interest.

1091
01:18:19,370 --> 01:18:21,777
I brung my checkbook with me.

1092
01:18:27,949 --> 01:18:30,963
- You own one share?
- I do. I just bought it.

1093
01:18:31,336 --> 01:18:33,189
Now, that gives me the right
as a stockholder...

1094
01:18:33,202 --> 01:18:36,424
...to view the company's
equity records, doesn't it?

1095
01:18:45,959 --> 01:18:47,625
Governor, sir?

1096
01:19:44,498 --> 01:19:46,432
Miss Littlepaugh?

1097
01:19:55,809 --> 01:19:57,709
You're from the insurance company.

1098
01:19:58,111 --> 01:20:00,511
No, no, I'm not.

1099
01:20:00,680 --> 01:20:02,978
But I know about your brother's
insurance policy.

1100
01:20:05,085 --> 01:20:07,076
Not that there was much left on it
to collect.

1101
01:20:07,254 --> 01:20:10,052
He borrowed against it
almost down to nothing. Didn't he?

1102
01:20:10,457 --> 01:20:12,516
Which means you lied...

1103
01:20:12,692 --> 01:20:14,489
...for almost nothing.

1104
01:20:14,861 --> 01:20:18,627
Now, don't you go
jumping out a window.

1105
01:20:19,366 --> 01:20:21,061
It wasn't the money...

1106
01:20:21,234 --> 01:20:23,327
...it was the disgrace.

1107
01:20:23,503 --> 01:20:25,937
I wanted him buried in the good part
of the cemetery...

1108
01:20:26,606 --> 01:20:29,006
...not in the back,
with all the sinners.

1109
01:20:29,176 --> 01:20:31,303
Why did he kill himself?

1110
01:20:31,611 --> 01:20:36,571
They drove him to it.
To make room for that thief, Irwin.

1111
01:20:37,584 --> 01:20:39,916
My brother went
to the Justice Department...

1112
01:20:40,086 --> 01:20:43,055
...and told them he knew
all about their man Irwin...

1113
01:20:43,223 --> 01:20:44,713
...and the bribes...

1114
01:20:44,891 --> 01:20:46,222
...but they wouldn't listen.

1115
01:20:49,196 --> 01:20:52,563
- Are you lying to me?
- No, that's what killed him.

1116
01:20:52,966 --> 01:20:55,230
He wrote the letter to me
and told me.

1117
01:20:55,402 --> 01:20:57,768
And then that night he... .

1118
01:20:58,738 --> 01:21:02,936
All right, wait. What letter?

1119
01:21:03,109 --> 01:21:05,509
The letter he wrote me
explaining it all.

1120
01:21:05,679 --> 01:21:09,080
The lawsuit Irwin was paid
to let up on...

1121
01:21:09,249 --> 01:21:11,444
...and how the power company
hid the payoffs...

1122
01:21:11,618 --> 01:21:15,520
...by firing my brother
and giving Irwin his job.

1123
01:21:17,357 --> 01:21:19,325
Where's the letter now?
What happened to it?

1124
01:21:19,492 --> 01:21:20,925
Oh, I have it.

1125
01:21:21,828 --> 01:21:23,261
Kept it all this time?

1126
01:21:25,999 --> 01:21:28,229
You have the letter here?

1127
01:21:33,640 --> 01:21:35,665
<i>You bring down the lion...</i>

1128
01:21:35,842 --> 01:21:37,901
<i>... the rest of the jungle
will quake in fear...</i>

1129
01:21:38,078 --> 01:21:39,943
<i>... and they'll all fall into line.</i>

1130
01:21:42,015 --> 01:21:44,813
Your employer is calling you, Jack.

1131
01:21:51,391 --> 01:21:53,450
Thank you.

1132
01:22:25,025 --> 01:22:26,458
Hello.

1133
01:22:26,726 --> 01:22:28,591
Hello, Anne.

1134
01:22:32,732 --> 01:22:35,701
- What's that?
- Orange soda.

1135
01:22:35,869 --> 01:22:37,131
Two straws.

1136
01:22:38,338 --> 01:22:42,138
- I think I might want something else.
- I didn't say one of them was for you.

1137
01:22:42,876 --> 01:22:45,868
It's the way it's drunk. Tradition.

1138
01:22:49,916 --> 01:22:53,682
- I know you went to see Adam.
- I did. What of it?

1139
01:22:53,853 --> 01:22:55,912
What did you say to him?

1140
01:22:56,089 --> 01:23:00,150
I went there and I offered him a job.
No use blaming me.

1141
01:23:00,327 --> 01:23:02,887
- I'm not blaming you.
- Well, that's what it sounds like.

1142
01:23:03,063 --> 01:23:07,056
That's what you sound like.
If you could hear yourself.

1143
01:23:07,233 --> 01:23:09,326
I want him to take it.
I want you to go back...

1144
01:23:09,502 --> 01:23:11,595
...and ask him again.

1145
01:23:12,339 --> 01:23:16,435
Jack, you know how it is.
My brother is the son of a governor...

1146
01:23:16,609 --> 01:23:19,373
...the grandson of a senator,
the great-grandson of a general.

1147
01:23:19,546 --> 01:23:24,609
<i>She wasn't telling me anything
I didn't already know about Adam.</i>

1148
01:23:25,452 --> 01:23:27,750
<i>But she was doing it
walking next to me...</i>

1149
01:23:27,921 --> 01:23:30,446
<i>... which is all that mattered.</i>

1150
01:23:31,491 --> 01:23:35,723
<i>So I let her go on
as long as she wanted.</i>

1151
01:23:37,797 --> 01:23:41,130
<i>I knew that Adam
had already made his decision.</i>

1152
01:23:41,301 --> 01:23:45,032
<i>He had decided to take the job
when I first brought it up.</i>

1153
01:23:45,739 --> 01:23:49,266
<i>He was just putting some time
between my visit and now...</i>

1154
01:23:49,442 --> 01:23:51,569
<i>... out of pride.</i>

1155
01:23:53,513 --> 01:23:56,038
He needs to do this
to be part of something himself...

1156
01:23:56,216 --> 01:23:57,513
...before he disappears.

1157
01:23:57,684 --> 01:24:01,313
<i>But something about
what she was saying bothered me.</i>

1158
01:24:01,621 --> 01:24:04,146
<i>The way an off-stage noise
bothers you.</i>

1159
01:24:04,324 --> 01:24:05,689
What kind of life is that?

1160
01:24:05,859 --> 01:24:07,486
<i>Something you hear- -</i>

1161
01:24:07,660 --> 01:24:08,888
He's a guardian of dead men.

1162
01:24:09,062 --> 01:24:11,121
<i>- but not clear enough
to catch the meaning of.</i>

1163
01:24:11,297 --> 01:24:14,824
I want him to take it.
He has to do it.

1164
01:24:15,001 --> 01:24:17,401
<i>So you push it aside.</i>

1165
01:24:24,477 --> 01:24:27,037
I guess that's one of your gunmen
I've heard about.

1166
01:24:27,213 --> 01:24:28,441
Sugar Boy, hell, no.

1167
01:24:28,615 --> 01:24:30,810
He just carry that peashooter
for decoration.

1168
01:24:30,984 --> 01:24:34,215
I tell you one thing, though.
Ain't nobody can drive like him.

1169
01:24:38,091 --> 01:24:40,355
So, what do you think, doc?

1170
01:24:41,528 --> 01:24:43,996
I think it'll do the people of the state
some good...

1171
01:24:44,164 --> 01:24:46,462
...and get you some votes.

1172
01:24:46,666 --> 01:24:48,793
There's a lot of ways to get votes.
Cheaper ones.

1173
01:24:50,270 --> 01:24:51,999
So I understand.

1174
01:24:52,172 --> 01:24:54,072
Because there are some things
I understand.

1175
01:24:54,240 --> 01:24:57,334
And some things you don't.
Just like there's some I don't.

1176
01:24:57,510 --> 01:24:59,637
What I do know
is what makes the mare go.

1177
01:24:59,813 --> 01:25:02,145
And that you can always
make goodness out of badness.

1178
01:25:02,315 --> 01:25:05,113
- That would be two things.
- Them's the two things I know, then.

1179
01:25:05,285 --> 01:25:06,513
And both of them wrong.

1180
01:25:06,686 --> 01:25:09,985
No, neither one of them, sir.
I beg your pardon.

1181
01:25:10,156 --> 01:25:13,023
You can always make good from bad,
in all things.

1182
01:25:13,393 --> 01:25:14,792
In politics, poetry...

1183
01:25:14,961 --> 01:25:17,725
...everything in between.
Makes no difference.

1184
01:25:18,198 --> 01:25:20,530
A man writes a sonnet...

1185
01:25:20,700 --> 01:25:22,565
...and it's good.

1186
01:25:22,735 --> 01:25:24,464
Is it less good if it turns out...

1187
01:25:24,637 --> 01:25:27,401
...the dame he wrote it about
is married to someone else?

1188
01:25:27,574 --> 01:25:30,338
That his passion was illicit?

1189
01:25:31,511 --> 01:25:33,741
Come on,
I wanna show you something.

1190
01:25:35,014 --> 01:25:38,279
I wouldn't mind
understanding something, actually.

1191
01:25:39,319 --> 01:25:43,619
Lf, as you say, there's only bad
to start with from conception on...

1192
01:25:43,790 --> 01:25:45,587
...and that good must be made
from bad...

1193
01:25:45,758 --> 01:25:47,749
...then how do you ever know
what the good is?

1194
01:25:48,495 --> 01:25:51,953
Well, that's simple.
You just make it up as you go along.

1195
01:25:52,131 --> 01:25:53,359
Make up what?

1196
01:25:53,533 --> 01:25:55,364
The good. What else
are we talking about?

1197
01:25:55,835 --> 01:25:57,564
Make it up as you go along?

1198
01:25:57,737 --> 01:26:00,205
Yeah. Just like folks have been doing
for a million years.

1199
01:26:00,373 --> 01:26:02,500
Since we fall out of trees,
crawl out the swamp.

1200
01:26:02,675 --> 01:26:04,233
They just cook up what is right.

1201
01:26:04,410 --> 01:26:06,970
If nobody likes that, well,
just cook it up again...

1202
01:26:07,146 --> 01:26:08,807
...a little different with a lid on.

1203
01:26:08,982 --> 01:26:10,210
And you know what?

1204
01:26:10,383 --> 01:26:12,943
Things under a lid
don't look no different than things...

1205
01:26:13,119 --> 01:26:14,950
...not under a lid
when there's one on it.

1206
01:26:15,121 --> 01:26:17,919
You don't have to convince me
of anything, Mr. Stark.

1207
01:26:18,091 --> 01:26:21,254
You've already done that.
I'm here, aren't I?

1208
01:26:21,694 --> 01:26:25,562
That's right.
And you're a good boy too, doc.

1209
01:26:25,732 --> 01:26:27,893
A lot better than you think.

1210
01:26:28,268 --> 01:26:30,395
So goddamn it.

1211
01:26:31,104 --> 01:26:35,131
Don't let none of them bastards
tell you no different.

1212
01:26:45,084 --> 01:26:48,144
I got a question since everybody's
trying to understand everything...

1213
01:26:48,321 --> 01:26:50,016
...all of a sudden.

1214
01:26:51,157 --> 01:26:52,385
Back when we met...

1215
01:26:53,226 --> 01:26:55,217
...at Slade's old place,
when we shook hands--

1216
01:26:55,395 --> 01:26:56,953
Do you remember that moment?

1217
01:26:57,130 --> 01:26:58,654
Like it was yesterday.

1218
01:26:59,866 --> 01:27:02,460
Did you or did you not
give me a wink?

1219
01:27:02,902 --> 01:27:04,927
A wink?

1220
01:27:07,340 --> 01:27:11,106
Well, that's just gonna have to remain
a mystery.

1221
01:27:11,277 --> 01:27:13,837
- You don't remember.
- Sure I do.

1222
01:27:15,148 --> 01:27:17,013
Then...?

1223
01:27:22,522 --> 01:27:24,183
You know, I... .

1224
01:27:24,357 --> 01:27:28,157
I just do recall giving you a wink.

1225
01:27:29,495 --> 01:27:32,293
But then,
maybe I got something in my eye...

1226
01:27:32,465 --> 01:27:34,990
...which would make it more
of a blink.

1227
01:27:36,703 --> 01:27:38,933
Did you have something
in your eye?

1228
01:27:40,273 --> 01:27:42,298
What if I didn't?

1229
01:27:42,909 --> 01:27:44,433
What would that mean?

1230
01:27:44,744 --> 01:27:46,371
That maybe you figured
you and me...

1231
01:27:46,546 --> 01:27:49,037
...had something in common
the others didn't.

1232
01:27:50,650 --> 01:27:55,451
Well, I'm not gonna tell you
and deprive you of the mystery.

1233
01:27:56,222 --> 01:28:00,716
There's just too few honest-to-God
mysteries left to go around.

1234
01:28:04,864 --> 01:28:07,856
And long after I'm dead and gone...

1235
01:28:08,635 --> 01:28:13,595
...and long after these sons of bitches
are dead and gone...

1236
01:28:13,773 --> 01:28:17,004
...I'm talking eternally now...

1237
01:28:18,578 --> 01:28:23,538
...the Willie Stark Hospital
will still be standing.

1238
01:28:24,050 --> 01:28:27,884
Where every man,
woman and child...

1239
01:28:28,054 --> 01:28:31,080
...who's sick or in pain can go in...

1240
01:28:31,257 --> 01:28:34,021
...knowing they'll get
all a man can do.

1241
01:28:34,193 --> 01:28:38,789
Not as charity,
but as a right, as your right!

1242
01:28:38,965 --> 01:28:43,163
As it is that every child
shall have a complete education!

1243
01:28:43,336 --> 01:28:48,672
That no person, aged or infirm,
shall want or beg for bread!

1244
01:28:48,841 --> 01:28:52,675
That no poor man's land
or house will be taxed!

1245
01:28:52,845 --> 01:28:56,042
That you shall not be deprived
of hope!

1246
01:29:02,488 --> 01:29:05,048
And if any man...

1247
01:29:05,892 --> 01:29:08,861
...stands between me...

1248
01:29:09,462 --> 01:29:11,896
...and fulfilling your rights...

1249
01:29:12,065 --> 01:29:15,159
...I will strike him down...

1250
01:29:15,334 --> 01:29:17,928
...so help me God!

1251
01:29:18,104 --> 01:29:22,473
Hip, shin, thigh and neck bone,
I will hit him.

1252
01:29:22,642 --> 01:29:25,110
I will hit him with a meat ax.

1253
01:29:25,278 --> 01:29:27,508
Somebody give me a meat ax...

1254
01:29:27,680 --> 01:29:31,138
...and bring me another one
for my friend and ally!

1255
01:29:31,718 --> 01:29:36,155
Because it's not only God's only son
with us on this one.

1256
01:29:36,322 --> 01:29:40,315
It's the son of the last
great leader of this state:

1257
01:29:40,493 --> 01:29:45,795
Governor Joe Stanton's boy,
Dr. Adam Stanton!

1258
01:30:02,749 --> 01:30:06,014
All right. See there?

1259
01:30:06,185 --> 01:30:09,586
It's not so bad.
It's not gonna kill you.

1260
01:30:30,042 --> 01:30:31,737
What's up?

1261
01:30:32,745 --> 01:30:34,110
Sadie.

1262
01:30:39,952 --> 01:30:41,943
Now he's done it.

1263
01:30:43,623 --> 01:30:46,421
He's done it again,
and I swear this time... .

1264
01:30:46,592 --> 01:30:49,322
- Done?
- Don't act so dumb.

1265
01:30:49,495 --> 01:30:52,692
Or any dumber than you are.
He's two-timing me again.

1266
01:30:52,865 --> 01:30:55,356
Or four or one or whatever timing
you wanna call it...

1267
01:30:55,535 --> 01:30:57,662
...because you're such a smartass.

1268
01:30:57,837 --> 01:31:00,931
- She skate?
- Shut up.

1269
01:31:01,307 --> 01:31:04,640
You and your friends.
Your highbrow friends.

1270
01:31:04,811 --> 01:31:07,006
All the money and privilege
and everything else...

1271
01:31:07,180 --> 01:31:11,378
...you pretend means nothing.
To someone with it, it means nothing.

1272
01:31:13,352 --> 01:31:15,513
Don't look so dumb.
I said it annoys me.

1273
01:31:15,688 --> 01:31:18,156
I have no idea
what you're talking about...

1274
01:31:18,324 --> 01:31:21,418
...or what it was tangled you two up
in the first place, love or hate.

1275
01:31:21,594 --> 01:31:23,061
You know what I'm talking about.

1276
01:31:23,229 --> 01:31:25,424
Maybe you fixed it up.
I'm sure you did.

1277
01:31:25,598 --> 01:31:27,725
Surely he's fixed you up,
like that pathetic...

1278
01:31:27,900 --> 01:31:30,425
...crazy brother of hers,
to say thanks.

1279
01:31:30,603 --> 01:31:35,472
"Thanks, Jack.
She is a looker, I do declare.

1280
01:31:35,641 --> 01:31:38,132
I'm naming you SDP,
yes, sir.

1281
01:31:38,311 --> 01:31:41,007
State Director of Pimps."

1282
01:31:43,883 --> 01:31:45,407
What are you saying?

1283
01:31:49,121 --> 01:31:50,918
Are you saying...?

1284
01:32:01,434 --> 01:32:02,662
Thank you.

1285
01:32:05,771 --> 01:32:07,568
Are you s--?

1286
01:33:16,208 --> 01:33:18,676
<i>I love you.</i>

1287
01:33:36,696 --> 01:33:38,857
We're gonna walk some more.

1288
01:33:43,135 --> 01:33:44,898
All right.

1289
01:33:57,650 --> 01:33:59,345
Hello.

1290
01:33:59,518 --> 01:34:00,917
Hello, Mother.

1291
01:34:01,253 --> 01:34:04,188
Yes, Mother. Yes.

1292
01:34:08,828 --> 01:34:10,523
All right.

1293
01:34:10,963 --> 01:34:12,726
All right, Mother.

1294
01:34:12,898 --> 01:34:14,729
Goodbye.

1295
01:34:21,340 --> 01:34:23,706
She and the Peytons
and the bridge partner...

1296
01:34:23,876 --> 01:34:26,743
...are going to La Grange
for a nightcap.

1297
01:35:02,481 --> 01:35:05,814
- Jackie.
- What?

1298
01:35:07,720 --> 01:35:09,813
I came up here.

1299
01:35:28,007 --> 01:35:31,101
<i>This was years ago,
you understand.</i>

1300
01:35:32,378 --> 01:35:35,836
<i>Back when things
weren't set in concrete.</i>

1301
01:35:37,383 --> 01:35:40,978
<i>Back when you had a way
of changing the course of things.</i>

1302
01:35:41,554 --> 01:35:43,488
<i>If you knew how.</i>

1303
01:35:46,759 --> 01:35:48,886
<i>She was perfect.</i>

1304
01:35:50,029 --> 01:35:52,395
<i>She had always been perfect.</i>

1305
01:35:53,399 --> 01:35:55,890
<i>I wanted to keep her that way...</i>

1306
01:35:56,669 --> 01:35:58,967
<i>... and like this.</i>

1307
01:36:00,372 --> 01:36:03,364
<i>To be young and older...</i>

1308
01:36:04,043 --> 01:36:05,806
<i>... somehow.</i>

1309
01:36:10,783 --> 01:36:14,241
<i>Of course that's not
what it looked like to her.</i>

1310
01:36:17,656 --> 01:36:19,783
<i>When I came home
from school at Christmas...</i>

1311
01:36:19,959 --> 01:36:22,223
<i>... we saw each other, of course.</i>

1312
01:36:22,394 --> 01:36:25,727
<i>We talked about things,
but never that.</i>

1313
01:36:25,898 --> 01:36:28,731
<i>We talked about love in general.</i>

1314
01:36:28,901 --> 01:36:32,667
<i>Like it was the subject of an essay
instead of real.</i>

1315
01:36:33,939 --> 01:36:38,842
<i>She said it was like jumping off
the high dive, love was.</i>

1316
01:36:39,278 --> 01:36:42,213
<i>Or like almost getting drowned.</i>

1317
01:36:42,681 --> 01:36:44,512
<i>Which, honestly,
I didn't understand.</i>

1318
01:36:46,385 --> 01:36:48,478
<i>For a long time.</i>

1319
01:36:52,725 --> 01:36:55,956
<i>You wanna know the reason
I stopped that night?</i>

1320
01:36:56,629 --> 01:36:58,927
<i>It wasn't nobility.</i>

1321
01:36:59,098 --> 01:37:01,566
<i>That's only what I told myself.</i>

1322
01:37:01,967 --> 01:37:04,959
We have all the time
in the world, right?

1323
01:37:12,945 --> 01:37:15,709
<i>It was that I knew something
was about to be taken from us...</i>

1324
01:37:16,782 --> 01:37:21,151
<i>... leaving in its place
something we didn't know.</i>

1325
01:37:22,454 --> 01:37:25,014
<i>Which didn't make her sad...</i>

1326
01:37:25,991 --> 01:37:27,959
<i>... but it did me.</i>

1327
01:37:29,929 --> 01:37:34,332
<i>You only get a couple of moments
that determine your life.</i>

1328
01:37:35,501 --> 01:37:37,799
<i>Sometimes only one.</i>

1329
01:37:39,338 --> 01:37:41,203
<i>And then it's gone.</i>

1330
01:37:44,476 --> 01:37:46,205
<i>Forever.</i>

1331
01:37:49,181 --> 01:37:52,048
I talked to Senator Loden
this morning.

1332
01:37:52,218 --> 01:37:55,119
He said you find something nice
to put on his plate...

1333
01:37:55,287 --> 01:37:58,586
...he might come around.
Vote any way you like.

1334
01:37:58,757 --> 01:38:00,748
While you cut yourself a slice.

1335
01:38:01,527 --> 01:38:03,961
- I ain't saying that.
- I know what you're saying, Tiny.

1336
01:38:04,129 --> 01:38:06,324
You know, I'd rather bust a man
than buy him.

1337
01:38:07,066 --> 01:38:11,730
- Well, that's up to you now.
- Yeah, sure is. Now go on. Get.

1338
01:38:22,948 --> 01:38:26,406
Do you have
any information for me?

1339
01:38:29,121 --> 01:38:31,783
You sure there's not something
you neglected to mention?

1340
01:38:31,957 --> 01:38:33,822
Something you forgot?

1341
01:38:35,861 --> 01:38:37,419
Jack.

1342
01:38:39,431 --> 01:38:40,898
No.

1343
01:38:41,600 --> 01:38:43,090
Nothing.

1344
01:38:45,170 --> 01:38:46,603
Nothing. Well.

1345
01:38:47,640 --> 01:38:51,508
How about that, Sugar? Nothing.
Am I alone in this?

1346
01:38:51,677 --> 01:38:53,577
The bastards
are pounding at the gate...

1347
01:38:53,746 --> 01:38:56,340
...they're gonna put a vote
of impeachment on the calendar!

1348
01:38:56,515 --> 01:38:58,847
They take that vote today, I'm out!

1349
01:39:04,056 --> 01:39:06,923
I need Judge Irwin with me.

1350
01:39:08,127 --> 01:39:10,891
Or at least not against me.

1351
01:39:16,368 --> 01:39:18,962
So whatever it is...

1352
01:39:19,238 --> 01:39:21,331
...that you don't have on him...

1353
01:39:25,811 --> 01:39:27,540
...use it.

1354
01:39:31,016 --> 01:39:33,450
I'm sorry, what did you say?

1355
01:39:33,619 --> 01:39:36,452
I said I'm going over to the judge's.

1356
01:39:37,222 --> 01:39:41,158
Well, you mean later.
He'll be napping this time of day.

1357
01:39:41,327 --> 01:39:43,261
There isn't any time
he'll wanna hear...

1358
01:39:43,429 --> 01:39:44,726
...what I have to tell him.

1359
01:39:46,498 --> 01:39:49,092
He's not well, you know.

1360
01:39:51,170 --> 01:39:53,104
I can't help that.

1361
01:39:54,473 --> 01:39:57,203
I do wish
you wouldn't get mixed up in things.

1362
01:39:58,110 --> 01:40:00,840
It isn't me mixed up in them.

1363
01:40:01,714 --> 01:40:03,579
The judge is napping right now,
Mr. Burden.

1364
01:40:03,749 --> 01:40:06,309
I'll wait in his study
until he comes down.

1365
01:40:17,429 --> 01:40:20,023
Fire this marble.

1366
01:40:22,000 --> 01:40:24,434
Watch the chandelier.

1367
01:40:25,137 --> 01:40:26,604
Okay, you can fire.

1368
01:40:29,308 --> 01:40:32,903
Hello, Jack. I didn't know
you were at your mother's.

1369
01:40:33,078 --> 01:40:34,568
- You just get in?
- Last night.

1370
01:40:35,114 --> 01:40:39,346
Yeah. It's a bit early in the day,
but what do you think?

1371
01:40:39,518 --> 01:40:42,385
A touch of bourbon
never hurt anyone.

1372
01:40:42,554 --> 01:40:43,782
Least not you and me.

1373
01:40:44,022 --> 01:40:47,389
We're indestructible, aren't we,
you and me?

1374
01:40:47,559 --> 01:40:50,221
- No, thanks.
- "No, thanks," he says.

1375
01:40:50,629 --> 01:40:53,359
Begging the question,
as the old man pours just one drink...

1376
01:40:53,532 --> 01:40:55,261
...what's on your mind?

1377
01:40:56,902 --> 01:40:58,631
Out with it.

1378
01:40:59,204 --> 01:41:01,035
You know who I work for.

1379
01:41:01,206 --> 01:41:02,571
How could I forget?

1380
01:41:03,008 --> 01:41:06,034
But let's just sit
and pretend that I have.

1381
01:41:06,278 --> 01:41:07,643
Come sit over here with me.

1382
01:41:19,825 --> 01:41:22,293
The truth is I don't hold
the same low opinion of him...

1383
01:41:22,461 --> 01:41:24,053
...as many of our friends
on the Row.

1384
01:41:24,229 --> 01:41:25,753
I was almost for him at one time.

1385
01:41:25,931 --> 01:41:30,891
He was busting out windowpanes
and, yeah, letting in some fresh air.

1386
01:41:31,069 --> 01:41:35,199
But now I am worried about him
knocking down the whole house.

1387
01:41:35,374 --> 01:41:38,207
So you threw in with his enemies
after you said you wouldn't.

1388
01:41:38,377 --> 01:41:39,901
Oh, Jack.

1389
01:41:40,112 --> 01:41:42,137
What is politics
but a matter of choices?

1390
01:41:42,314 --> 01:41:45,078
You make a choice knowing there's
a chance it's the wrong one.

1391
01:41:45,250 --> 01:41:48,378
You've made a choice
and you know how much it's cost you.

1392
01:41:48,554 --> 01:41:50,852
There's always a price
for everything we do.

1393
01:41:52,257 --> 01:41:55,021
When we came by that night
and were leaving...

1394
01:41:55,194 --> 01:41:56,786
...you said you would think
about it.

1395
01:41:56,962 --> 01:41:59,897
About calling off the dogs?
No, I did not say that.

1396
01:42:00,065 --> 01:42:02,898
Your memory is faulty, sir.
He said, "Think about it"...

1397
01:42:03,068 --> 01:42:04,296
...which I don't have to.

1398
01:42:04,470 --> 01:42:06,734
I don't have to think
about things I already know.

1399
01:42:06,905 --> 01:42:09,499
You should think it over.
Even now...

1400
01:42:09,675 --> 01:42:12,473
...because it's not too late.

1401
01:42:16,348 --> 01:42:18,213
Too late for what?

1402
01:42:22,254 --> 01:42:23,846
Hey, Jack.

1403
01:42:24,656 --> 01:42:26,214
Jesus.

1404
01:42:26,925 --> 01:42:29,393
- What is it?
- Just say you'll back Stark...

1405
01:42:29,561 --> 01:42:31,324
...against these attacks.
- No!

1406
01:42:36,735 --> 01:42:39,568
Now, that has the sound of finality,
don't it?

1407
01:42:39,738 --> 01:42:42,434
- Yes, it does.
- Yeah.

1408
01:43:12,838 --> 01:43:15,773
You know,
I find this difficult to believe.

1409
01:43:15,941 --> 01:43:17,806
For me too.

1410
01:43:18,410 --> 01:43:21,902
And that your boss would even think
he could pressure me.

1411
01:43:22,080 --> 01:43:23,570
Could blackmail me.

1412
01:43:23,815 --> 01:43:28,843
- The first word is better.
- The first word is prettier, not better.

1413
01:43:29,888 --> 01:43:34,484
Don't you know that this stuff
wouldn't stand up? Not in any court.

1414
01:43:34,660 --> 01:43:36,958
It happened almost 25 years ago.

1415
01:43:37,129 --> 01:43:38,619
You couldn't get any testimony...

1416
01:43:39,331 --> 01:43:41,891
...except from that woman
who is related...

1417
01:43:42,067 --> 01:43:45,764
...and whose testimony,
if she gave it...

1418
01:43:46,038 --> 01:43:48,063
...would be worthless.

1419
01:43:49,141 --> 01:43:51,837
And everybody else, Jack...

1420
01:43:53,412 --> 01:43:55,710
...everybody else is dead.

1421
01:43:56,915 --> 01:43:58,610
You're not.

1422
01:43:59,184 --> 01:44:02,153
You're not dead.
And you don't live in any court.

1423
01:44:02,321 --> 01:44:05,518
You live in the world, where people
think you're a certain kind of man.

1424
01:44:05,691 --> 01:44:07,682
I am a certain kind of man.

1425
